data.content:
Your test works but has weak assertions — every check uses `Assert.IsTrue`, which gives unhelpful failure messages like "Expected: True, Actual: False". MSTest has dedicated APIs for this.

**Key improvements:**

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Assert exact count — clear failure message showing expected vs actual
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);

    // Assert all elements satisfy a condition
    CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(users);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive), 
        "Expected all users to be active");

    // Assert a specific element exists
    Assert.IsTrue(users.Any(u => u.Role == "Admin"), 
        "Expected an Admin user in results");
}
```

**MSTest collection assertion cheat sheet:**

| Instead of | Use | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(list.Count == 3)` | `Assert.AreEqual(3, list.Count)` | Shows "Expected:3 Actual:5" on failure |
| `Assert.IsTrue(a.SequenceEqual(b))` | `CollectionAssert.AreEqual(a, b)` | Shows which element differs |
| checking items aren't null manually | `CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(list)` | Built-in, clearer intent |
| checking no duplicates manually | `CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreUnique(list)` | Built-in |
| `Assert.IsTrue(list.Contains(x))` | `CollectionAssert.Contains(list, x)` | Shows the missing item |

**Other `CollectionAssert` methods:** `AreEquivalent` (same items, any order), `IsSubsetOf`, `DoesNotContain`.

**Pro tip:** Always add a message string to `Assert.IsTrue` when testing LINQ expressions — without it, failures are undiagnosable.
